docs.abstract: The Vermont senator won the endorsement of the United Electrical workers, a group that has long supported him, as Democratic candidates continue to seek backing from labor.
docs.snippet: The Vermont senator won the endorsement of the United Electrical workers, a group that has long supported him, as Democratic candidates continue to seek backing from labor.
docs.lead_paragraph: PITTSBURGH — The United Electrical, Radio and Machine Workers of America endorsed Bernie Sanders on Monday, offering one of the few endorsements by a national union as Democratic presidential candidates continue to court labor’s support.

headline.main: Candidates Are Jockeying for Union Endorsements. Bernie Sanders Just Got One.
headline.print_headline: Electrical Workers Union Throws Support to Sanders

docs.abstract: The Democratic front-runner repeatedly invoked President Barack Obama’s name, while some of his rivals said the party needed to move well beyond the policies of the last Democratic president.
docs.snippet: The Democratic front-runner repeatedly invoked President Barack Obama’s name, while some of his rivals said the party needed to move well beyond the policies of the last Democratic president.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. clung tightly to the legacy of the Obama administration in a Democratic primary debate on Thursday, asking voters to view him as a stand-in for the former president as an array of progressive challengers, led by Senators Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders, brandished more daring policy promises and questioned Mr. Biden’s political strength.

headline.main: Attacks on Biden in Debate Highlight Divide Over the Obama Legacy
headline.print_headline: Invoking Obama,  Biden Jabs Back  At Progressives

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: The candidates were asked about a wide range of topics over three hours, but abortion and the gender pay gap never came up.

docs.lead_paragraph: In a nearly three-hour debate, the Democratic candidates clashed on health care policy differences, offered varying plans to combat the scourge of gun violence and even discussed whether Americans should switch to a vegan diet to help mitigate the effect of farming on climate change (short answer: no).

headline.main: Marathon Democratic Debate Includes No Questions About Women’s Issues

byline.original: By Nick Corasaniti and Matt Stevens

docs.abstract: In New York, Senator Elizabeth Warren described a government compromised by the influence of the wealthy. President Trump, in New Mexico, denounced a “failed liberal establishment.”
docs.snippet: In New York, Senator Elizabeth Warren described a government compromised by the influence of the wealthy. President Trump, in New Mexico, denounced a “failed liberal establishment.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren stood beneath a marble arch in New York City, telling a crowd of thousands that she would lead a movement to purge the government of corruption. Not far from the site of a historic industrial disaster, Ms. Warren described Washington as utterly compromised by the influence of corporations and the extremely wealthy, and laid out a detailed plan for cleansing it.

headline.main: Warren and Trump Speeches Lay Out Competing Visions of Populism
headline.print_headline: They Agree on Fighting Corruption, but Not on What’s Corrupt

docs.abstract: Leana Wen, who was fired in July as Planned Parenthood president after less than a year on the job, is at odds with the group over the terms of her departure and the group’s direction.

docs.lead_paragraph: Leana Wen, the recently fired former president of Planned Parenthood, appears headed toward an increasingly contentious exit, after accusing the organization’s leadership of trying to “buy my silence” in a dispute that threatens to prolong and magnify an acrimonious transition at the top of the nation’s best known women’s health care and reproductive rights group.

headline.main: Planned Parenthood and Fired Former Chief Mired in Escalating Dispute

docs.abstract: The Galivants Ferry Stump speaking event in South Carolina has been held every two years for at least 143 years. Now, for the first time, it will host Democratic presidential candidates.
docs.snippet: The Galivants Ferry Stump speaking event in South Carolina has been held every two years for at least 143 years. Now, for the first time, it will host Democratic presidential candidates.
docs.lead_paragraph: For more than a century, South Carolina Democrats seeking political office have traveled by horseback and automobile to a general store on the banks of the Pee Dee River to make their case to curious voters. Their destination: the biennial stump meeting in Galivants Ferry, S.C., which has been hosted by different generations of the same family since the late 1800s.

headline.main: At the Country’s Oldest Stump, a Presidential Twist

docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Kamala Harris of California, who is increasingly seeking to carve out an ideological lane separate from the most progressive Democrats running for president, laid out a new plan Monday for providing Medicare for all Americans, with a twist that stops short of the complete overhaul of the health insurance system that Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont has proposed.

headline.main: Kamala Harris Sets Up Debate Showdown on Health Care With New Plan
